<p><b>SEAT, S.A.</b> (<small>Spanish:&#160;</small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_Spanish" title="Help:IPA for Spanish">[ˈse.at]</a></span>, <i>Sociedad Española de Automóviles de Turismo</i>) is a Spanish <a href="/wiki/Automotive_industry" title="Automotive industry">automobile manufacturer</a> with its head office in <a href="/wiki/Martorell" title="Martorell">Martorell</a>, Spain.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup> It was founded on May 9, 1950, by the <i><a href="/wiki/Instituto_Nacional_de_Industria" title="Instituto Nacional de Industria">Instituto Nacional de Industria</a></i> (INI), a state-owned industrial holding company.</p>
<p>It is currently a wholly owned subsidiary of the German <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Group" title="Volkswagen Group">Volkswagen Group</a>.</p>
<p>The headquarters of SEAT, S.A. are located at SEAT's industrial complex in <a href="/wiki/Martorell" title="Martorell">Martorell</a> near <a href="/wiki/Barcelona" title="Barcelona">Barcelona</a>, Spain. By 2000 annual production peaked at over 500,000 units; in total up to 2006, over 16 million cars have been produced<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup> including more than 6 million from the Martorell plant,<sup id="cite_ref-SEAT_Today_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SEAT_Today-5">[5]</a></sup> with three-quarters of the annual production being exported to over seventy countries worldwide.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup></p>
<p></p>

<p></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Facilities">Facilities</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Facilities">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:F%C3%A0brica_SEAT_Martorell.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/F%C3%A0brica_SEAT_Martorell.JPG/220px-F%C3%A0brica_SEAT_Martorell.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/F%C3%A0brica_SEAT_Martorell.JPG/330px-F%C3%A0brica_SEAT_Martorell.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/F%C3%A0brica_SEAT_Martorell.JPG/440px-F%C3%A0brica_SEAT_Martorell.JPG 2x" data-file-width="3648" data-file-height="2736" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:F%C3%A0brica_SEAT_Martorell.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
SEAT's industrial complex in Martorell</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>SEAT today is the only major Spanish car manufacturer with the ability and the infrastructure to develop its own cars in-house.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template noprint Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTRS" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NOTRS"><span title="This claim needs references to better sources. (November 2016)">better&#160;source&#160;needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Martorell">Martorell</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Martorell">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Its headquarters and main manufacturing facilities are located in <a href="/wiki/Martorell" title="Martorell">Martorell</a>, an industrial town located some 30 kilometres northwest of <a href="/wiki/Barcelona" title="Barcelona">Barcelona</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup> with a production capacity of around 500,000 units per annum.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup> The plant was opened by <a href="/wiki/Juan_Carlos_I_of_Spain" title="Juan Carlos I of Spain">King Juan Carlos of Spain</a> on February 22, 1993, and replaced SEAT's former assembly plant by the coast in <a href="/wiki/Barcelona_Free_Port" class="mw-redirect" title="Barcelona Free Port">Barcelona's freeport zone (Zona Franca)</a>. A rail connection between SEAT's Martorell and Zona Franca complexes facilitates vehicle and parts transportation between the two sites.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-al2017_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-al2017-11">[11]</a></sup></p>
<p>The industrial complex in Martorell also hosts the facilities of <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Sport" title="SEAT Sport">SEAT Sport</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> SEAT's Technical Center, Research and Development Center (R&amp;D),<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> Design Center,<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> Prototypes Centre of Development,<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup> SEAT Service Center (also incorporating the After-Sales Service division, the Customer Services division and the Catalunya Motor dealership),<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> as well as the Genuine Parts Centre for SEAT, Volkswagen, Audi and Škoda brands.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Zona_Franca">Zona Franca</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Zona Franca">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Centre_de_Formaci%C3%B3_de_la_Seat-_a1.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Centre_de_Formaci%C3%B3_de_la_Seat-_a1.jpg/220px-Centre_de_Formaci%C3%B3_de_la_Seat-_a1.jpg" width="220" height="293" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Centre_de_Formaci%C3%B3_de_la_Seat-_a1.jpg/330px-Centre_de_Formaci%C3%B3_de_la_Seat-_a1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Centre_de_Formaci%C3%B3_de_la_Seat-_a1.jpg/440px-Centre_de_Formaci%C3%B3_de_la_Seat-_a1.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1944" data-file-height="2592" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Centre_de_Formaci%C3%B3_de_la_Seat-_a1.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
SEAT's Training Centre in Barcelona's Zona Franca.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The development and assembly facilities are some of the newest and most modern and efficient within the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Group" title="Volkswagen Group">Volkswagen Group</a>, giving the SEAT Martorell site the ability to produce high-quality cars<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup> not only for its own brand but also for other Volkswagen Group brands, such as <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen" title="Volkswagen">Volkswagen</a> and <a href="/wiki/Audi" title="Audi">Audi</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup> For example, the development and design of several Audi models (e.g. the <a href="/wiki/Audi_A1" title="Audi A1">Audi A1</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup> the <a href="/wiki/Audi_A3" title="Audi A3">Audi A3</a> Sportback,<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup> the <a href="/wiki/Audi_Q5" title="Audi Q5">Audi Q5</a> etc.) and also several Audi development projects took place there,<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup> and from 2011 onwards the Martorell plant manufactures the <a href="/wiki/Audi_Q3" title="Audi Q3">Audi Q3</a> small SUV.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup></p>
<p>The Barcelona Zona Franca site includes the SEAT Training Centre,<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup> the Zona Franca Press Shop factory, producing stamped body parts, and the Barcelona Gearbox del Prat plant, producing gearboxes not only for SEAT but also for other <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Group" title="Volkswagen Group">Volkswagen Group</a> marques (<a href="/wiki/VW" class="mw-redirect" title="VW">VW</a>, <a href="/wiki/Audi" title="Audi">Audi</a> and <a href="/wiki/%C5%A0koda_Auto" title="Škoda Auto">Škoda</a>);<sup id="cite_ref-Gearbox_del_Prat_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gearbox_del_Prat-25">[25]</a></sup> the latter plant was awarded the Volkswagen Excellence Award in 2009 by the Volkswagen Group for high-quality production process and product.<sup id="cite_ref-Gearbox_del_Prat_25-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gearbox_del_Prat-25">[25]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Others">Others</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Others">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Another plant owned directly by SEAT from 1975<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup> was the Landaben plant in <a href="/wiki/Pamplona" title="Pamplona">Pamplona</a>, but in December 1993 its ownership was transferred to the Volkswagen Group subsidiary "Volkswagen-Audi-Espana, S.A.",<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup> and the site today is producing Volkswagen cars in Spain.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup> However, SEAT's Martorell site still provides support to Volkswagen's operations in the Pamplona plant when necessary, as it did after a serious fire in the paint shop in the Landaben VW plant in April 2007.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:SEATpavAutostadt.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/SEATpavAutostadt.JPG/220px-SEATpavAutostadt.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/SEATpavAutostadt.JPG/330px-SEATpavAutostadt.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/SEATpavAutostadt.JPG/440px-SEATpavAutostadt.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2592" data-file-height="1944" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:SEATpavAutostadt.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
SEAT's Pavilion at Autostadt, Wolfsburg.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Factories of the Volkswagen Group currently producing SEAT models also include the <a href="/wiki/Bratislava" title="Bratislava">Bratislava</a> site in <a href="/wiki/Slovakia" title="Slovakia">Slovakia</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Palmela" title="Palmela">Palmela</a> <a href="/wiki/AutoEuropa" title="AutoEuropa">AutoEuropa</a> factory in <a href="/wiki/Portugal" title="Portugal">Portugal</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-SEAT_Today_5-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SEAT_Today-5">[5]</a></sup> while in the past other plants were involved too in producing SEAT models, such as the factories in Germany (Wolfsburg) and Belgium.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup> Future plans include a new Research and development (R&amp;D) centre in the city of <a href="/wiki/Barcelona" title="Barcelona">Barcelona</a> in the field of environmental and energy efficiency for the entire Volkswagen Group and also the launch of a project on the city's urban mobility,<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup> as well as a SEAT museum in the Zona Franca's 'Nave A122' site hosting all production and prototype models ever presented by SEAT together with some special or limited edition vehicles with historical value for the brand and the automotive history of Spain.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">[33]</a></sup></p>
<p>Among SEAT's subsidiaries, the SEAT Deutschland GmbH subsidiary company is based in Mörfelden-Walldorf, Germany, and apart from its commercial activities has the further responsibility of operating SEAT's electronic platform, the SEAT IT Services Network.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">[34]</a></sup> In <a href="/wiki/Wolfsburg" title="Wolfsburg">Wolfsburg</a>, Germany, in the middle of a lake inside the <a href="/wiki/Autostadt" title="Autostadt">Autostadt</a>, the Volkswagen Group's corporate theme park,<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup> is SEAT's thematic pavilion, one of the largest pavilions in the park.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Presence_in_different_markets">Presence in different markets</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Presence in different markets">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Seat_600_Competici%C3%B3n.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Seat_600_Competici%C3%B3n.jpg/220px-Seat_600_Competici%C3%B3n.jpg" width="220" height="146" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Seat_600_Competici%C3%B3n.jpg/330px-Seat_600_Competici%C3%B3n.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Seat_600_Competici%C3%B3n.jpg/440px-Seat_600_Competici%C3%B3n.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2048" data-file-height="1360" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Seat_600_Competici%C3%B3n.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/SEAT_600" title="SEAT 600">SEAT 600</a>, the first model exported by SEAT in 1965 to <a href="/wiki/Colombia" title="Colombia">Colombia</a>, became the best-selling car in <a href="/wiki/Finland" title="Finland">Finland</a> from 1970 to 1973.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In its 60 years, there was only a short period from 1953 to 1965 when the firm produced its cars exclusively for the domestic Spanish market. In 1965 and in a rather symbolic move, the company exported some 150 units of its SEAT 600 model destined for Colombia by air freight for the first time, until two years later in 1967 SEAT reached a deal over the renegotiation of its licence contract with Fiat which allowed the Spanish firm to form an international distribution network for its cars and thereafter start its export operations massively to more than twelve different countries, entering the export market in 1969. Until the early 1980s, however, most SEAT exports were sold with Fiat badging.<sup id="cite_ref-SEATint_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SEATint-37">[37]</a></sup> As a response to SEAT's bid for independence, Fiat committed themselves to selling 200,000 SEAT-built cars a year from 1981, compared to 120,000 the year before. At the end of 1983, just after SEAT had won its legal battle with Fiat, a quarter of the production went to Egypt and Latin America.<sup id="cite_ref-seidler35_38-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-seidler35-38">[38]</a></sup> In Europe, they were represented in West Germany, Belgium, France, Italy, Austria, and Greece. The UK, Ireland, and various Scandinavian markets were planned to be added in 1984. This was in spite of the company only being able to export the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Ronda" title="SEAT Ronda">Ronda</a>, with the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Fura" title="SEAT Fura">Fura</a> to follow.<sup id="cite_ref-SEATint_37-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SEATint-37">[37]</a></sup></p>
<p>To date, the company has launched its own models in more than 70 countries worldwide in accordance with the development policies of the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Group" title="Volkswagen Group">Volkswagen Group</a>, with almost three-quarters of its annual production representing exports for the markets out of Spain. Its core market remains <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a>, while the most successful market outside of Europe in terms of sales for SEAT is currently <a href="/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>, where the company has dealer presence in 27 Mexican states.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">[39]</a></sup></p>
<p>In Europe the brand has been launched in almost 40 countries across <a href="/wiki/Northern_Europe" title="Northern Europe">Northern</a>, <a href="/wiki/Western_Europe" title="Western Europe">Western</a>, <a href="/wiki/Southern_Europe" title="Southern Europe">Southern</a>, <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Europe" title="Eastern Europe">Eastern Europe</a> and <a href="/wiki/Russia" title="Russia">Russia</a>. SEAT today also sells its cars in 11 countries in <a href="/wiki/Asia" title="Asia">Asia</a>, mostly in the <a href="/wiki/Middle_East" title="Middle East">Middle East</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Arabian_peninsula" class="mw-redirect" title="Arabian peninsula">Arabian peninsula</a>, in 16 countries in <a href="/wiki/Americas" title="Americas">Americas</a> including <a href="/wiki/North_America" title="North America">North America</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Caribbean_Sea" title="Caribbean Sea">Caribbean Sea</a>, <a href="/wiki/Central_America" title="Central America">Central America</a> and <a href="/wiki/South_America" title="South America">South America</a>, and finally <a href="/wiki/Africa" title="Africa">Africa</a>, mainly in <a href="/wiki/North_Africa" title="North Africa">North Africa</a>. Some of its cars have been sold outside <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a>, branded as <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen" title="Volkswagen">Volkswagens</a>, such as the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Ibiza" title="SEAT Ibiza">SEAT Ibiza</a> hatchback, known in <a href="/wiki/South_Africa" title="South Africa">South Africa</a> as the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Polo_Playa" title="Volkswagen Polo Playa">Volkswagen Polo Playa</a>, the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Inca" title="SEAT Inca">SEAT Inca</a> panel van as the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Caddy" title="Volkswagen Caddy">Volkswagen Caddy</a>, or the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba" title="SEAT Córdoba">SEAT Córdoba</a>, also known as the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Polo" title="Volkswagen Polo">Volkswagen Polo Classic</a>.</p>
<p>In the years to come SEAT plans expanding in even more markets, the most crucial of them all being <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup> While in the past SEAT held talks with the Chinese car maker FAW in order to form an alliance for the local production of SEAT models in China-located plants, the present project to enter the Chinese market comprises in 2012 first to start selling its range with cars produced in SEAT's Spain-located Martorell plant, followed later in a second phase by the local assembly of SEAT models in China.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup></p>
<p>SEAT's further expansion plans in more markets outside of Europe have yet to be realised. In the past the company was considering a possible launch in the United States although this move has never been carried out.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">[42]</a></sup> Rumours also of a SEAT model being sold as a Volkswagen in <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canada</a> and the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> to supplement the Volkswagen's brand lineup there have occasionally circulated, but have always been unsubstantiated, and ultimately proven to be false.</p>
<p>In the past other market areas where the brand was also present for a short time were <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">Australia</a> and <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">New Zealand</a> (from 1995 to 1999) as well as <a href="/wiki/South_Africa" title="South Africa">South Africa</a> (from June 2006 to the end of 2008), however the brand was withdrawn from those markets due to Volkswagen's decision citing that current and expected circumstances made the ongoing importation of a niche brand non-viable.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup> SEAT has been present in the Russian Federation since 2007, In India all Volkswagen group brands are assembled or imported except SEAT.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Establishment_of_SEAT">Establishment of SEAT</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Establishment of SEAT">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Spain is the world's eighth largest producer of automobiles and its car market stands among the largest in Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">[45]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup> However, this has not always been the case; in the first half of the 20th century, Spain's economy was relatively underdeveloped compared to other western European countries and had a limited automobile market. In this period there was only limited car production and only a few low volume local manufacturers catering mainly to the luxury end of the market, of which <a href="/wiki/Hispano-Suiza" title="Hispano-Suiza">Hispano-Suiza</a> was the most successful. Spain's limited market for mass-produced vehicles was taken over by foreign companies operating through subsidiaries that either imported cars or assembled cars from imported parts, depriving the country of the technological know-how and large investments needed for mass production. The situation greatly deteriorated with the <a href="/wiki/Spanish_Civil_War" title="Spanish Civil War">Spanish Civil War</a> of 1936 to 1939. Car demand collapsed, not only due to the greatly reduced purchasing power of Spaniards caused by war devastation but also because the multinational subsidiaries either ceased operations or were severely stricken by the war and its aftermath.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Classic_Seat_1400._Sign.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Classic_Seat_1400._Sign.jpg/220px-Classic_Seat_1400._Sign.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Classic_Seat_1400._Sign.jpg/330px-Classic_Seat_1400._Sign.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Classic_Seat_1400._Sign.jpg/440px-Classic_Seat_1400._Sign.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4272" data-file-height="2848" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Classic_Seat_1400._Sign.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
SEAT's first emblem.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The lack of interest shown by the foreign firms in the weakened post civil war Spanish market opened an opportunity for local interests.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">[48]</a></sup> SEAT dates its origins back to June 22, 1940 when the Spanish bank '<a href="/wiki/Banco_Sabadell" title="Banco Sabadell">Banco Urquijo</a>', with the support of a group of industrial companies, (<a href="/wiki/Hispano-Suiza" title="Hispano-Suiza">Hispano-Suiza</a>, Basconia, Duro-Felguera, S.E. de Construcción Naval, <a href="/wiki/Euskalduna" title="Euskalduna">Euskalduna</a>, S.E. de Construcciones Metálicas, Fundiciones Bolueta, Echevarría etc.) founded the 'Sociedad Ibérica de Automóviles de Turismo' (S.I.A.T.) with the goal of establishing Spain's own mass production car maker. The initial Banco Urquijo's project aimed at running the S.I.A.T. motor company as a fully private enterprise but soon after 1941 the interventionist state holding company <a href="/wiki/Instituto_Nacional_de_Industria" title="Instituto Nacional de Industria">Instituto Nacional de Industria</a> (INI) following a decision taken by the Franco government on January 3, 1942.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">[49]</a></sup> The goal for the new national car brand was not to be only another licensee car maker assembling foreign designs and parts in Spain, but of developing the whole manufacturing process from design to assembly within Spain. Because of the country's lack of expertise in automotive mass-production development, it was decided to find a foreign partner who would contribute technically and with its own models in the early years in exchange for cash, shares, bonds and royalties. With the rest of Europe having entered the <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a>, and Spain itself in ruins from its civil war, the project was delayed but not abandoned due to its strategic importance.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:JoseOrtizEchag%C3%BCePhotoLab.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/JoseOrtizEchag%C3%BCePhotoLab.jpg/220px-JoseOrtizEchag%C3%BCePhotoLab.jpg" width="220" height="233" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/JoseOrtizEchag%C3%BCePhotoLab.jpg/330px-JoseOrtizEchag%C3%BCePhotoLab.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/JoseOrtizEchag%C3%BCePhotoLab.jpg/440px-JoseOrtizEchag%C3%BCePhotoLab.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1663" data-file-height="1763" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:JoseOrtizEchag%C3%BCePhotoLab.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Ortiz-Echag%C3%BCe" title="José Ortiz-Echagüe">José Ortiz-Echagüe Puertas</a>, SEAT's first ever president, was in 1976 made honorary president for life.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>SEAT under its current name was founded on May 9, 1950 under the denomination 'Sociedad Española de Automóviles de Turismo, S.A.' (S.E.A.T.) by the Instituto Nacional de Industria (INI) with a starting capital of 600 million <a href="/wiki/Spanish_peseta" title="Spanish peseta">pesetas</a> — equivalent today of almost 3.6 million Euros — in the form of 600 thousand shares of one thousand Pesetas each, and in a time when the country was in need of remodelling the fundamental structures in its national economy, just after the end of the World War II. The birth of SEAT came almost a year and a half after the Spanish government and six Spanish banks ('Banco Urquijo', '<a href="/wiki/Banesto" title="Banesto">Banco Español de Crédito (Banesto)</a>', '<a href="/wiki/Banco_Bilbao_Vizcaya_Argentaria" title="Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria">Banco de Bilbao</a>', '<a href="/wiki/Banco_Bilbao_Vizcaya_Argentaria" title="Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria">Banco de Vizcaya</a>', 'Banco Hispano-Americano' and 'Banco Central') had signed on October 26, 1948 an alliance contract with the Italian car manufacturer <a href="/wiki/Fiat" class="mw-redirect" title="Fiat">Fiat</a> so as to form a partnership with a foreign ally in order to bring to life Spain's major car manufacturer.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">[50]</a></sup> The favoured bidders were Germany's Volkswagen and Italy's Fiat. Fiat's bid won for several reasons including Fiat's prominence in Spain and the fact that the company established the short-lived 'Fiat Hispania' plant in <a href="/wiki/Guadalajara,_Spain" class="mw-redirect" title="Guadalajara, Spain">Guadalajara</a>, which was destroyed in the Spanish Civil War. Fiat's collaboration with the French company <a href="/wiki/Simca" title="Simca">Simca</a> proved Fiat's ability to manage complex international projects. Fiat's experience in the semi-protected car market in Italy was seen as the most easily transferable to the one in Spain, both of which had, at the time, customers of low incomes and limited markets for cars, as well as similar road conditions. In Italy, Fiat dominated the market for vehicles under 12 horsepower, which would initially be the main market segment in Spain. The relative economic isolation of World War II damaged Italy and made Fiat interested in opportunities outside Italy, meaning that the negotiations with the Italian manufacturer could prosper more easily in favour of Spanish interests than with those from other countries. In 1947, the Banco Urquijo group had revived the S.I.A.T. project and in the next year the talks ended successfully with the signing of a three-part contract, with the understanding that the INI would hold a 51% controlling interest as well as a ruling act in the new company preserving a focused approach of the enterprise in the 'national interest'. The Banco Urquijo group, although a minority share holder, looked forward to assuming a leading role in the future as soon as the company was privatesed. Partner car maker Fiat was offered a 7% share in exchange of its technical assistance. This way SEAT not only would be able to reinitiate the country's economic recovery and as the largest employer in the 1960s and 1970s but would also contribute to the industrialisation of what was still a largely rural eoconomy.</p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:06_SEAT_zona_franca,_amb_els_laboratoris_a_la_dreta.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/06_SEAT_zona_franca%2C_amb_els_laboratoris_a_la_dreta.jpg/220px-06_SEAT_zona_franca%2C_amb_els_laboratoris_a_la_dreta.jpg" width="220" height="117" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/06_SEAT_zona_franca%2C_amb_els_laboratoris_a_la_dreta.jpg/330px-06_SEAT_zona_franca%2C_amb_els_laboratoris_a_la_dreta.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/06_SEAT_zona_franca%2C_amb_els_laboratoris_a_la_dreta.jpg/440px-06_SEAT_zona_franca%2C_amb_els_laboratoris_a_la_dreta.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2272" data-file-height="1206" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:06_SEAT_zona_franca,_amb_els_laboratoris_a_la_dreta.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
SEAT's Barcelona Zona Franca site and laboratories.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Even though there were initial thoughts of locating in less developed inland cities like <a href="/wiki/Valladolid" title="Valladolid">Valladolid</a> and <a href="/wiki/Burgos" title="Burgos">Burgos</a>, it was decided that the company's plant would be constructed in the duty-free zone area of the Port of Barcelona (Barcelona Zona Franca), which would offer better access to the Mediterranean shipping and the rest of Europe through rail and road connections across the nearby French border. Barcelona was after all a city with an industrial history that had built up expertise in complex industrial enterprises since the latter part of the 19th century; it was also the host location of many early historical Spanish car makers, like <a href="/wiki/Hispano-Suiza" title="Hispano-Suiza">Hispano-Suiza</a> and <a href="/wiki/Elizalde_(automobile)" title="Elizalde (automobile)">Elizalde</a>, and subsidiaries of foreign car makers, like 'Ford Motor Ibérica' and 'General Motors Peninsular'. Being an enterprise of vital interest for the national economy as well as an investment opportunity for Fiat's expansion plans through the Iberian peninsula, SEAT benefitted from state tariff and tax exemptions and technical assistance from its foreign partner Fiat. The company’s first President was the industrial and aeronautical engineer, pilot and photographer <a href="/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Ortiz-Echag%C3%BCe" title="José Ortiz-Echagüe">José Ortiz-Echagüe Puertas</a>, who came from the Spanish aircraft manufacturer <a href="/wiki/Construcciones_Aeron%C3%A1uticas_SA" title="Construcciones Aeronáuticas SA">Construcciones Aeronáuticas SA</a> where he had held the position of <a href="/wiki/CEO" class="mw-redirect" title="CEO">CEO</a>, and who in 1976 was meant to be named the <i>Honorary lifetime president of SEAT</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">[51]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">[52]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">[53]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Partnership_with_Fiat">Partnership with Fiat</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Partnership with Fiat">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Seat1400.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Seat1400.jpg/170px-Seat1400.jpg" width="170" height="169" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Seat1400.jpg/255px-Seat1400.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Seat1400.jpg/340px-Seat1400.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1234" data-file-height="1225" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Seat1400.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/SEAT_1400" title="SEAT 1400">SEAT 1400</a>, the first model produced by SEAT in 1953.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The construction works for SEAT's Zona Franca plant began on 1950 and the opening day came three years later on June 5, 1953, while in the meantime since 1951 the Spanish marque was starting preparations for setting up almost from scratch an entire supplier industry background. The first car in the marque's history to be produced was a <a href="/wiki/SEAT_1400" title="SEAT 1400">SEAT 1400</a> model that came off the production line on November 13, 1953 with licence plate 'B-87.223'. In the following few months the plant's production output and workforce would significally increase together with the implementation of locally made components in the production process, in order to limit imports from one part and from another part to push to the development of the almost non-existent Spanish supplier industry and meet SEAT's assigned key role as the national car maker in restoring the Spanish economy of the post World War II Spain. By 1954 the use of Spanish-made parts had risen to 93% of the total and next year on May 5, 1955 the factory was officially opened. Nevertheless, the impact to the Spanish society could not be seen clear immediately, since the first model launched by SEAT was considered a luxury car therefore it was highly priced and still not affordable to the average Spanish consumer. Consequently, SEAT needed a second more economical model to compete against simpler inexpensive designs that appeared in the local market, like the <a href="/wiki/Bisc%C3%BAter" title="Biscúter">Biscúter</a>, which seemed to suit better to the unwealthy customers looking for a personal mean of transport in a suffering economic environment.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">[54]</a></sup></p>
<p>Until the time SEAT had the technical maturity and expertise to present its first self-developed model the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_1200_Sport" title="SEAT 1200 Sport">SEAT 1200 Sport</a> in 1975, in its beginnings the company had to manufacture either rebadged or restyled models borrowed from the range of its Italian partner <a href="/wiki/Fiat_Automobiles" title="Fiat Automobiles">Fiat Automobiles</a>, or even redeveloped them according to the needs of its own range. However the first example of a SEAT exclusive derivative would arrive already on September 1963 with the launch of the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_800" class="mw-redirect" title="SEAT 800">SEAT 800</a>, a car which was developed in-house by SEAT with no equivalent model in Fiat's range on the basis of the SEAT 600 as a stretched version with 4-doors.</p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Monumento_al_Seat_600_._Fuengirola_-_Espa%C3%B1a.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Monumento_al_Seat_600_._Fuengirola_-_Espa%C3%B1a.jpg/220px-Monumento_al_Seat_600_._Fuengirola_-_Espa%C3%B1a.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Monumento_al_Seat_600_._Fuengirola_-_Espa%C3%B1a.jpg/330px-Monumento_al_Seat_600_._Fuengirola_-_Espa%C3%B1a.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Monumento_al_Seat_600_._Fuengirola_-_Espa%C3%B1a.jpg/440px-Monumento_al_Seat_600_._Fuengirola_-_Espa%C3%B1a.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2816" data-file-height="2112" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Monumento_al_Seat_600_._Fuengirola_-_Espa%C3%B1a.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
A monument in Spain for the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_600" title="SEAT 600">SEAT 600</a>, a symbol of the <a href="/wiki/Spanish_miracle" title="Spanish miracle">Spanish miracle</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">[55]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">[56]</a></sup></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 1957 SEAT founded the SEAT Training Centre in the greater Zona Franca plant area, an institution covering the training of qualified personnel and serving the needs of the automobile industry in specialized technical human resources.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">[57]</a></sup> In that same year was launched the historical <a href="/wiki/SEAT_600" title="SEAT 600">SEAT 600</a>, which proved to be the crucial car that literally motorized Spain, being the first car for many Spanish families and becoming a symbol of the <a href="/wiki/Spanish_Miracle" class="mw-redirect" title="Spanish Miracle">Spanish Miracle</a>.</p>
<p>As the growth of the annual production was hitting one record after another due to the heavy demand, the economies of scale achieved would permit cutting costs and prices, subsequently renew demand and boost sales together with profits for SEAT. On June 29, 1964, the brand opened its new headquarters in <a href="/wiki/Madrid" title="Madrid">Madrid</a>, which hosted the firm's sole — up to 1972 — general administration offices. In Barcelona was found only SEAT's plant manager until 1973, a year when SEAT settled in Catalonia another general direction.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Seat_850_Sport_Jarama_2006.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Seat_850_Sport_Jarama_2006.JPG/220px-Seat_850_Sport_Jarama_2006.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Seat_850_Sport_Jarama_2006.JPG/330px-Seat_850_Sport_Jarama_2006.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Seat_850_Sport_Jarama_2006.JPG/440px-Seat_850_Sport_Jarama_2006.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2048" data-file-height="1536" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Seat_850_Sport_Jarama_2006.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/SEAT_850" title="SEAT 850">SEAT 850 Sport</a>, launched in 1967,<br />
it was the first <a href="/wiki/Coup%C3%A9" title="Coupé">coupé</a> model from SEAT.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 1967, fourteen years after producing cars for the domestic market, SEAT's success was signaled by its dominant position in Spain, ahead of its major competitors, i.e. '<a href="/wiki/FASA-Renault" title="FASA-Renault">FASA-Renault</a>', 'Citroën-Hispania', <a href="/wiki/Authi" title="Authi">Authi</a> and <a href="/wiki/Barreiros_(manufacturer)" title="Barreiros (manufacturer)">Barreiros</a>, making SEAT the Spain's largest auto-maker in sales numbers and a wholly localized production. In that year an agreement between Fiat and the Spanish Ministry of Industry was reached so as to put an end in the restrictions over exporting SEAT cars out of Spain, a term of the original licensee contract agreed with Fiat in 1948. In exchange for that, Fiat would increase its holding in the company from 7% to 36%, and at the same time the share held by the <a href="/wiki/Instituto_Nacional_de_Industria" title="Instituto Nacional de Industria">government holding agency</a> would be reduced from a controlling 51% to 32%. The remaining 32% was taken by the six major Spanish banks, decreased from their previous 42% share split equally in 7% parts owned by every single one of them. Although not a majority owner, Fiat now was seen to control the business: the deal also included various undertakings by Fiat to help in the growth of SEAT, and with the development of a new model (possibly the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_133" title="SEAT 133">SEAT 133</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-Autocar1967_58-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Autocar1967-58">[58]</a></sup> On December 6, 1967, SEAT also founded its own customer financing company 'Financiera SEAT, S.A.' (Fiseat).</p>
<p>To be able to produce independently its own research projects, SEAT on November 16, 1970 came in accordance with Fiat so as to start building separate infrastructures aiming at developing new technologies. As the brand arranged in 1972 some provisional facilities in the site of the future Technical Center in Martorell and in 1973 began construction works, this goal would only take five years till 1975 to be reached with the completion of the first phase in the construction of SEAT's Technical Center, a facility designed by the Catalan architect <a href="/wiki/Josep_Antoni_Coderch" title="Josep Antoni Coderch">Josep Antoni Coderch</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">[59]</a></sup></p>
<p>During the same period, the manufacturer continued to dominate the Spanish auto market, producing 282,698 cars — more than 58% of the Spanish production total — in 1971 despite disruption that year caused by strikes and a serious flood at the coastally sited Barcelona plant.<sup id="cite_ref-Motor197204_60-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Motor197204-60">[60]</a></sup> However, with just 81 cars per thousand people, Spanish car sales were seen as ripe for further growth, and SEAT faced the prospect of increased competition with other major manufacturers contemplating establishment or expansion of 'local' production facilities in the still heavily protected Spanish car market.<sup id="cite_ref-Motor197204_60-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Motor197204-60">[60]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 1973, SEAT and 'Citroën-Hispania' jointly contributed equal shares in founding the <a href="/wiki/Vigo" title="Vigo">Vigo</a>-located factory of 'Industrias Mecánicas de Galicia, SA' (Indugasa) producing <a href="/wiki/Constant-velocity_joint" title="Constant-velocity joint">constant-velocity joints</a>, essential components used in <a href="/wiki/Front-wheel_drive" title="Front-wheel drive">front-wheel drive</a> cars i.e. in a transmission layout the use of which was becoming more and more common at the time. This plant — which in the next years would supply parts not only to SEAT and 'Citroën-Hispania' but also to 'Ford España' — was meant to be transferred later in 1986 to the multinational company <a href="/wiki/GKN" title="GKN">GKN</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">[61]</a></sup></p>
<p>On May 1975, after a request from the Spanish state authorities to ensure the rescue of the jobs for the workers in the <a href="/wiki/Authi" title="Authi">Authi</a> owned factories, SEAT moved on talks with the parent company <a href="/wiki/British_Leyland" title="British Leyland">British Leyland Motor Corporation (BLMC)</a> of the bankrupt Authi in order to take over the brand's operations in Spain leaving aside <a href="/wiki/General_Motors" title="General Motors">GM</a>'s interest in it, something which would otherwise open the path for the American automaker to enter the Spanish market thus jeopardizing the relationship with Fiat. The talks ended soon on July 1975, when an agreement was announced between the two parts under which SEAT would acquire from BLMC the Authi brand along with its assets for 1,250 million pesetas. The imposed acquisition of the Landaben plant would also result in giving up SEAT's plans to build a new facility in <a href="/wiki/Saragossa" class="mw-redirect" title="Saragossa">Saragossa</a>. Although the Authi supplier factory in Manresa was transferred to a company called Cometsa for 150 million pesetas, the Landaben plant in Pamplona remained under SEAT's ownership to continue production on February 1976 only of SEAT cars this time.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62">[62]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">[63]</a></sup></p>
<p>The 1970s were a decade of rising prosperity in Spain, which is reflected in the announcement in August 1976 that SEAT would commence local production of the <a href="/wiki/Lancia_Beta" title="Lancia Beta">Lancia Beta</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Autocar197608_64-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Autocar197608-64">[64]</a></sup> Three years later Beta production by SEAT indeed commenced at the company's recently acquired Pamplona plant, though only the Coupe and HPE lift-back versions were included. The Spanish cars were fitted with a simplified suspension system and smaller engines than their Italian counterparts in order to qualify for a lower car tax rate.</p>
<p>In 1977 SEAT's leasing company Liseat was founded and in 1979 the Gearbox del Prat facility was set up as a specialised plant in the production of gearboxes, gear mechanisms and differentials in El Prat del Llobregat near Barcelona.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Dispute_with_Fiat">Dispute with Fiat</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Dispute with Fiat">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In the early 1980s, extensive discussions concerning funding and control took place between SEAT's major shareholder, the Spanish government, and <a href="/wiki/Fiat" class="mw-redirect" title="Fiat">Fiat Automobiles</a>; SEAT needed major capital investment, which Fiat was not prepared to contribute, partially due to the oil crisis of the 1970s and in also due to the uncertainty for Fiat's interests following the end of a protectionist policy against GM in Spain. The outcome, in 1982, was an end to the relationship with Fiat after nearly 30 years, a rather surprising decision in spite of the favourable perspectives for the Spanish economy with Spain being in the anteroom of the <a href="/wiki/European_Economic_Community" title="European Economic Community">European Economic Community</a> since 1977.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Seat_Ronda_Front.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Seat_Ronda_Front.jpg/220px-Seat_Ronda_Front.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Seat_Ronda_Front.jpg/330px-Seat_Ronda_Front.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Seat_Ronda_Front.jpg/440px-Seat_Ronda_Front.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3264" data-file-height="2448" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Seat_Ronda_Front.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
SEAT Ronda</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The end of the co-operation with the Italian firm was marked by a change in SEAT's logo in 1982, and the first car under the new SEAT logo without Fiat involvement appeared in the same year, the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Ronda" title="SEAT Ronda">SEAT Ronda</a>, styled by Rayton Fissore in collaboration with the Technical Centre in Martorell. The launch of this model though sparked a lawsuit from Fiat against SEAT, as the former claimed the car was too similar to a car in Fiat's range, the <a href="/wiki/Fiat_Ritmo" title="Fiat Ritmo">Ritmo</a>. In defence of SEAT, the then president of SEAT, Juan Miguel Antoñanzas, showed a Ronda to the press with all the parts different from the Fiat Ritmo painted in bright yellow, to highlight the differences. The case was eventually taken to the Arbitration Chamber of Paris which in 1983 declared that differences between both cars were important enough so as not to consider the Ronda as a rebadged Ritmo, ending the dispute in favour of SEAT. Rumour at the time had it that Fiat was angry because the Ronda restyling was in fact too close to their own planned restyling for the Fiat Ritmo, which they had to scrap.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Volkswagen_Group_subsidiary">Volkswagen Group subsidiary</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Volkswagen Group subsidiary">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:SEATIbizaMk1SXI.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/SEATIbizaMk1SXI.jpg/220px-SEATIbizaMk1SXI.jpg" width="220" height="135" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/SEATIbizaMk1SXI.jpg/330px-SEATIbizaMk1SXI.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/SEATIbizaMk1SXI.jpg/440px-SEATIbizaMk1SXI.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1108" data-file-height="678" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:SEATIbizaMk1SXI.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/SEAT_Ibiza" title="SEAT Ibiza">SEAT Ibiza Mk1</a>. Launched in 1984,<br />
it was the first model developed by SEAT as an independent company, together with <a href="/wiki/Porsche" title="Porsche">Porsche</a> and <a href="/wiki/Karmann" title="Karmann">Karmann</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 1982, <a href="/wiki/Carl_Hahn" title="Carl Hahn">Dr. Carl Horst Hahn</a> — who had just assumed responsibility as the chairman of the Volkswagenwerk AG (<a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Group" title="Volkswagen Group">Volkswagen Group</a>) — examined the opportunity of approaching SEAT after Fiat's withdrawal, in his plan to expand the Volkswagen Group's operations out of Germany and turning the German group into a global force. It would also follow the precedent set by other global manufacturers (such as <a href="/wiki/Ford_Motor_Company" title="Ford Motor Company">Ford</a> in <a href="/wiki/Valencia" title="Valencia">Valencia</a> and <a href="/wiki/General_Motors" title="General Motors">General Motors</a> in <a href="/wiki/Zaragoza" title="Zaragoza">Zaragoza</a>) in setting up manufacturing operations in Spain. However, the Spanish authorities had already started talks with other foreign firms such as <a href="/wiki/Toyota" title="Toyota">Toyota</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">[65]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Nissan" title="Nissan">Nissan</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mitsubishi_Motors" title="Mitsubishi Motors">Mitsubishi</a><sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66">[66]</a></sup> in order to choose a strong partner for SEAT. But it was Hahn's interest that would soon result in an industrial and commercial cooperation as well as a license agreement with SEAT on September 30, 1982 for the production in Spain of the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Passat" title="Volkswagen Passat">Volkswagen Passat</a>-<a href="/wiki/VW_Santana" class="mw-redirect" title="VW Santana">Santana</a> and <a href="/wiki/VW_Polo" class="mw-redirect" title="VW Polo">Polo-Derby</a> models in SEAT's Zona Franca and Landaben factories respectively<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67">[67]</a></sup> — having thus as an effect on April 29, 1983 the ending of the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Panda" class="mw-redirect" title="SEAT Panda">SEAT Panda</a>'s production at the Landaben assembly lines due to need of adapting this plant to the production of the VW Polo — and eventually a partnership agreement was signed on June 16, 1983 between the two parts being represented by the president of SEAT Juan Miguel Antoñanzas and Carl Hahn on behalf of the Volkswagenwerk AG.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">[68]</a></sup> SEAT also gained the rights to distribute Volkswagens in Spain.<sup id="cite_ref-SEATint_37-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SEATint-37">[37]</a></sup></p>
<p>SEAT launched its new Ibiza, a <a href="/wiki/Giorgetto_Giugiaro" title="Giorgetto Giugiaro">Giugiaro</a> styled hatchback which made use of System Porsche engines and also featured underpinnings from the <a href="/wiki/Fiat_Ritmo" title="Fiat Ritmo">Fiat Ritmo/Strada</a>, in 1984. It also formed the basis of the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Malaga" class="mw-redirect" title="SEAT Malaga">Malaga</a>, a four-door family saloon. SEAT then began to expand into markets beyond Spain's borders, including the <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>, where it began selling cars in the autumn of 1985.</p>
<p>On June 18, 1986, after a purchase of the 51% majority stake of SEAT followed by the increase of its share up to 75% on December 23, the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Group" title="Volkswagen Group">Volkswagen Group</a> became the major <a href="/wiki/Shareholder" title="Shareholder">shareholder</a> of SEAT. On December 18, 1990 the Volkswagen Group acquired 99.99% <a href="/wiki/Ownership" title="Ownership">ownership</a> of the company, thus making SEAT the first non-German <a href="/wiki/Subsidiary" title="Subsidiary">wholly owned subsidiary</a> of the Group. Fulfilling Hahn's expectations, SEAT not only made a profit two years after Volkswagen bought a majority of its stock, but also provided a low-cost manufacturing outlet for other VW group models, contributing up to 15.2% of the VW group's total output in 1989 — as well as an opportunity to enter the relatively unexploited (at that time) Spanish market under the SEAT, VW and Audi names.</p>
<p>The gathering of the brand's main infrastructures in the greater Martorell plant area has taken place in a long process beginning back in 1975 with the opening of the SEAT Technical centre<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">[69]</a></sup> but it was only in 1989 when a decision was taken to start building a new main assembly facility next to the Technical Centre in Martorell replacing the old one in Zona Franca. In that same year began the translocation of SEAT's Madrid administration offices to Barcelona with the sale of two of the brand's assets in <a href="/wiki/Paseo_de_la_Castellana" title="Paseo de la Castellana">La Castellana</a> to be completed in 1991 with the definitive installation of SEAT's headquarters in the <a href="/wiki/Catalonia" title="Catalonia">Catalonia</a> region.</p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:SEAT_Toledo_1.6_Magnus_1998.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/SEAT_Toledo_1.6_Magnus_1998.jpg/220px-SEAT_Toledo_1.6_Magnus_1998.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/SEAT_Toledo_1.6_Magnus_1998.jpg/330px-SEAT_Toledo_1.6_Magnus_1998.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/SEAT_Toledo_1.6_Magnus_1998.jpg/440px-SEAT_Toledo_1.6_Magnus_1998.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1024" data-file-height="768" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:SEAT_Toledo_1.6_Magnus_1998.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/SEAT_Toledo" title="SEAT Toledo">SEAT Toledo Mk1</a>, launched in 1991,<br />
was the first model fully developed under Volkswagen Group's ownership.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The centralisation of the management, design, research and production facilities localized around the plant site was meant to serve the aim of optimising the development in the process of making new models. On February 22, 1993 <a href="/wiki/Juan_Carlos_I" class="mw-redirect" title="Juan Carlos I">King Juan Carlos of Spain</a> and the newly elected since January 1, 1993 Chairman of the Volkswagen Group <a href="/wiki/Ferdinand_Pi%C3%ABch" title="Ferdinand Piëch">Dr. Ferdinand Piëch</a> inaugurated the Martorell plant, one of the most modern and efficient car plants in Europe using the '<a href="/wiki/Just-in-time_(business)" class="mw-redirect" title="Just-in-time (business)">Just in time</a>' process with its suppliers’ site located only 2.5&#160;km away. The first cars that rolled out of the Martorell plant production lines were the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Ibiza" title="SEAT Ibiza">SEAT Ibiza Mk2</a> and its saloon version, the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba" title="SEAT Córdoba">SEAT Córdoba Mk1</a>. The new Ibiza was a huge success for SEAT, greatly expanding its market share particularly on export markets.</p>
<p>The original planning in October 1993 to close the emblematic Zona Franca assembly plant as soon as the production of vehicles would be transferred to the more efficient Martorell plant was overturned after an arrangement between the Spanish authorities and the Volkswagen Group, according to which the Zona Franca site would continue its operations but would be gradually turned into a site with an auxiliary role in the production process (foundry, press-shop etc.). Meanwhile, on December 23, 1993, the 'Fábrica Navarra de Automóviles, S.A.' was founded as a new company to hold the management of the Landaben factory separating any ties to SEAT in production matters, with its shares being transferred to Volkswagen on June 1994 over which however SEAT would regain ownership four years later in 1998.</p>
<p>In 1994 the Design Center in <a href="/wiki/Sitges" title="Sitges">Sitges</a><sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">[70]</a></sup> — the Spanish coastal town south of Barcelona — and the suppliers' park in Zona Franca were also inaugurated, and in winter of the same year SEAT's financing and leasing companies — Fiseat and Liseat — were sold to 'Volkswagen Financial Services AG'. During 1994, SEAT in collaboration with <a href="/wiki/Suzuki" title="Suzuki">Suzuki</a> manufactured a 5-door prototype model of a <a href="/wiki/City_car" title="City car">city car</a>, internally named as Rosé, aiming to replace with it the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Marbella" title="SEAT Marbella">Marbella</a> in its range, nevertheless this model never made it through to production.<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71">[71]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">[72]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba_SX_(coup%C3%A9).JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba_SX_%28coup%C3%A9%29.JPG/220px-SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba_SX_%28coup%C3%A9%29.JPG" width="220" height="159" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba_SX_%28coup%C3%A9%29.JPG/330px-SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba_SX_%28coup%C3%A9%29.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba_SX_%28coup%C3%A9%29.JPG/440px-SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba_SX_%28coup%C3%A9%29.JPG 2x" data-file-width="943" data-file-height="682" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba_SX_(coup%C3%A9).JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba" title="SEAT Córdoba">SEAT Córdoba SX</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Coup%C3%A9" title="Coupé">coupé</a> version of the Córdoba Mk1 <a href="/wiki/Saloon_(automobile)" class="mw-redirect" title="Saloon (automobile)">saloon</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The first time a SEAT model was manufactured out of Spain was in 1996, with the production of the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Alhambra" title="SEAT Alhambra">SEAT Alhambra Mk1</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Palmela" title="Palmela">Palmela</a> <a href="/wiki/AutoEuropa" title="AutoEuropa">AutoEuropa</a> plant in <a href="/wiki/Portugal" title="Portugal">Portugal</a>. Also on January 1997 it was the first time when a non-Spanish descendant, the Belgian Pierre-Alain de Smedt, was ever appointed SEAT's chairman. The <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Arosa" title="SEAT Arosa">SEAT Arosa</a>, a three-door city hatchback, was launched in 1997, effectively replacing the Marbella, SEAT's version of the <a href="/wiki/Fiat_Panda" title="Fiat Panda">Fiat Panda</a> which had been in production since the early 1980s.</p>
<p>On April 7, 1998 the Zona Franca plant marked the end in the production life cycle of the Marbella model, signalising an historical moment for SEAT with the end of vehicle production in SEAT's oldest factory opened in 1953; ever since the Zona Franca plant produces components and parts to be assembled in other locations. It also signaled the demise of SEAT's last Fiat-based model.</p>
<p>In March 1999 at the Geneva Motor Show, SEAT presented a modern stylised logo, more rounded compared to the last one and with the use of the silver colour on a red background — instead of the previous blue — symbolising respectively the rational and the emotional. This came shortly after the launch of the second generation Toledo, and shortly before the launch of the Toledo-based <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Leon" class="mw-redirect" title="SEAT Leon">Leon</a> hatchback.</p>
<p>The 'auto emoción' slogan was presented next year in September 2000 reflecting the brand's new youthful and sporty corporate identity, while <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Sport" title="SEAT Sport">SEAT Sport</a> apart from its motorsport activities would undertake the responsibility of developing SEAT's high-performance vehicles.</p>
<p>Next year on July 1, 2000 <a href="/wiki/Bernd_Pischetsrieder" title="Bernd Pischetsrieder">Dr. Bernd Peter Pischetsrieder</a>, the former <a href="/wiki/Chief_Executive_Officer" class="mw-redirect" title="Chief Executive Officer">Chief Executive Officer</a> of <a href="/wiki/BMW" title="BMW">BMW</a>, was appointed to head SEAT. In the spring of 2002 as Pischetsrieder was commissioned to chair the entire Volkswagen Group, he gave way to his German compatriot Andreas Schleef on March 7, 2002.</p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:SEAT_Leon_Cupra_Mk1-2.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/SEAT_Leon_Cupra_Mk1-2.jpg/220px-SEAT_Leon_Cupra_Mk1-2.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/SEAT_Leon_Cupra_Mk1-2.jpg/330px-SEAT_Leon_Cupra_Mk1-2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/SEAT_Leon_Cupra_Mk1-2.jpg/440px-SEAT_Leon_Cupra_Mk1-2.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3264" data-file-height="2448" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:SEAT_Leon_Cupra_Mk1-2.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/SEAT_Le%C3%B3n" title="SEAT León">SEAT León</a> Mk1 Cupra R</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>From 2002 up to 2007 SEAT formed part of the Audi Brand Group, the Volkswagen Group's automotive sub-division, consisted of Audi, SEAT and Lamborghini, that was focused on more sporty values, with the marque's product vehicles and performance being under the higher responsibility of the Audi brand.<sup id="cite_ref-C4Wauto-6671758_73-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-C4Wauto-6671758-73">[73]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74">[74]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2006 the new SEAT corporate head office was opened in Martorell and the Martorell SEAT Design Centre superseded the Volkswagen Group Design Centre Europe at <a href="/wiki/Sitges" title="Sitges">Sitges</a><sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75">[75]</a></sup> — which previously hosted the design facility jointly owned by SEAT, Volkswagen and Audi<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">[76]</a></sup> — as on February 23 of the same year an agreement over the transfer of the installations of the latter to the City of Sitges was closed, with the Martorell's Design Centre official opening on the other hand eventually taking place on December 30, 2007.</p>
<p>On January 12, 2007, there was the inauguration of the building of the SEAT Service Centre next to the southern entrance of the Martorell factory, the department focusing on technical support, after-sales and marketing purposes and also covering the feedback and the relationship of the brand with the customers and its worldwide network. On January 2007 began also operation the SEAT Prototypes Centre of Development located in the heart of the Martorell industrial complex, a facility inaugurated on July 16 of the same year, bringing together activities related to the virtual and physical preproduction process of new models (like prototyping, modeling, pilot product development and series analysis) thus shortening development times for prototypes and pre-production vehicles as well as saving costs with the use of modern technologies like virtual simulation.<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77">[77]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Motorsport">Motorsport</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Motorsport">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Sport" title="SEAT Sport">SEAT Sport</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Seat1430.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Seat1430.jpg/220px-Seat1430.jpg" width="220" height="141" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Seat1430.jpg/330px-Seat1430.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Seat1430.jpg/440px-Seat1430.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1290" data-file-height="828" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Seat1430.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The <a href="/wiki/SEAT_1430" title="SEAT 1430">SEAT 1430</a> in competition.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>SEAT's involvement in motorsport begins back in the 1970s with the brand's contribution to the national formula races in Spain and by the end of the same decade the start of its implication to rallies.<sup id="cite_ref-SEAT.27s_Racing_History_1970-1985_78-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SEAT.27s_Racing_History_1970-1985-78">[78]</a></sup> In 1971, the <i>'Special Vehicles department'</i> was formed with the mission to enforce the brand's participation in rally championships, followed by 11 titles between 1979 and 1983.<sup id="cite_ref-SEAT.27s_Racing_History_1970-1985_78-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SEAT.27s_Racing_History_1970-1985-78">[78]</a></sup> The year 1985 was the moment when <i><a href="/wiki/SEAT_Sport" title="SEAT Sport">SEAT Sport</a></i> was founded as a separate motorsport division and especially since the Volkswagen Group takeover in 1986, SEAT has been increasing even more its presence in the motorsport world, mainly down to VW's plan on focusing the SEAT brand as 'sporty' in order to appeal particularly to the younger generation of drivers.<sup id="cite_ref-SEAT_Sport_1987-2001_79-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SEAT_Sport_1987-2001-79">[79]</a></sup> The result of this effort has been rewarded through SEAT's most prestigious titles in <a href="/wiki/FIA" class="mw-redirect" title="FIA">FIA</a> championships, three conquests with the SEAT Ibiza Kit-Car in the FIA 2L <a href="/wiki/World_Rally_Championship" title="World Rally Championship">World Rally Championship (WRC)</a> (1996, 1997, 1998) and two times with the SEAT León in the FIA <a href="/wiki/World_Touring_Car_Championship" title="World Touring Car Championship">World Touring Car Championship (WTCC)</a> (2008, 2009).<sup id="cite_ref-SEAT_Sport_1987-2001_79-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SEAT_Sport_1987-2001-79">[79]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Rallying">Rallying</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Rallying">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>SEAT's first serious attempt at a <a href="/wiki/World_Rally_Championship" title="World Rally Championship">World Rally Championship</a> (WRC) was back in the <a href="/wiki/1977_World_Rally_Championship_season" class="mw-redirect" title="1977 World Rally Championship season">1977 season</a> when SEAT took part with its 'SEAT 1430/124D Especial 1800' race car, and already in its debut rallying event at the <a href="/wiki/Rallye_Automobile_Monte_Carlo" class="mw-redirect" title="Rallye Automobile Monte Carlo">Montecarlo Rally</a> the SEAT team finished in the third and fourth place with the official 1430-1800 cars being driven by Antonio Zanini and Salvador Cañellas. In the recent years the consignment was burdened on the small <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Ibiza" title="SEAT Ibiza">SEAT Ibiza</a>, a 1.6L normally aspirated <a href="/wiki/Front-wheel_drive" title="Front-wheel drive">front-wheel drive</a> car with its roots in the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Polo" title="Volkswagen Polo">Volkswagen Polo</a>. The Ibiza allowed the company to further evolve its rallying experience, and was officially engaged in some European national championships. The years went by until a 2L version of the Ibiza was <a href="/wiki/Homologation" title="Homologation">homologated</a> as a kit-car, and extra wide tracks, larger wheels, brakes, etc., were fitted to it as the <a href="/wiki/F%C3%A9d%C3%A9ration_Internationale_de_l%27Automobile" title="Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile">Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile</a> (FIA) kit-car regulations allow. With these attributes, the car succeeded three times the 2L <a href="/wiki/World_Champion" class="mw-redirect" title="World Champion">World Champion</a> ('96, '97, '98), proving its maker had accumulated enough experience, and budgets, to take a chance at the reign category, the <a href="/wiki/World_Rally_Car" title="World Rally Car">World Rally Car</a> class of rallying cars.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Sola_cangas.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Sola_cangas.jpg/220px-Sola_cangas.jpg" width="220" height="148" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Sola_cangas.jpg/330px-Sola_cangas.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5f/Sola_cangas.jpg 2x" data-file-width="388" data-file-height="261" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Sola_cangas.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Daniel_Sol%C3%A0" title="Daniel Solà">Daniel Solà</a> with the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba" title="SEAT Córdoba">SEAT Córdoba</a> WRC at the Rallye de tierra de Cangas del Narcea.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>SEATs three conquests of the FIA 2L WRC title, and the sport's popularity in Spain, probably convinced <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Group" title="Volkswagen Group">Volkswagen Group</a> management to go further and allow the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Sport" title="SEAT Sport">SEAT Sport</a> department a chance to reach its goal in the top class WRC category. This situation came to an end in September 2000, when the company's German upper management revoked its decision forcing SEAT Sport to retire from the World Rally Championship.</p>
<p>SEATs project to build a WRC-spec car was officially announced during the 1997 San Remo rally. It was in 1998 that the first evolution of the '<a href="/wiki/SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba" title="SEAT Córdoba">SEAT Córdoba</a> WRC' car was presented at the Porto Motor Show and then first enrolled by the company to compete at the highest level of WRC racing. The Córdoba was based on the family saloon of the same name but was, naturally, a WRC class car equipped with an <a href="/wiki/Inline-four_engine" title="Inline-four engine">inline-four</a> <a href="/wiki/Turbocharger" title="Turbocharger">turbocharged</a> <a href="/wiki/Petrol_engine" title="Petrol engine">petrol engine</a>, permanent <a href="/wiki/Four-wheel_drive" title="Four-wheel drive">four-wheel drive</a>, and active differentials involved in its transmission. The 'Córdoba WRC' made its debut at the 1998 <a href="/wiki/Rally_Finland" title="Rally Finland">Rally of Finland</a>, while a further development on the race car was incarnated on the 'SEAT Córdoba WRC E2' car which was presented at the Barcelona Motor Show in 1999. However, the short <a href="/wiki/Wheelbase" title="Wheelbase">wheelbase</a> and high-mounted <a href="/wiki/Internal_combustion" class="mw-redirect" title="Internal combustion">engine</a> (compared to its rivals) worked against the Córdoba, and results weren't top competing. Despite hiring ex-WRC champion <a href="/wiki/Didier_Auriol" title="Didier Auriol">Didier Auriol</a>, and a new <a href="/wiki/Evolution" title="Evolution">evolution</a> of the car i.e. the 'SEAT Córdoba WRC E3', SEAT pulled out of international rallying at the end of 2000.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Touring_cars">Touring cars</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Touring cars">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Yvan_Muller_and_Andy_Priaulx_2008_Japan.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Yvan_Muller_and_Andy_Priaulx_2008_Japan.jpg/220px-Yvan_Muller_and_Andy_Priaulx_2008_Japan.jpg" width="220" height="159" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Yvan_Muller_and_Andy_Priaulx_2008_Japan.jpg/330px-Yvan_Muller_and_Andy_Priaulx_2008_Japan.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Yvan_Muller_and_Andy_Priaulx_2008_Japan.jpg/440px-Yvan_Muller_and_Andy_Priaulx_2008_Japan.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1280" data-file-height="925" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Yvan_Muller_and_Andy_Priaulx_2008_Japan.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Yvan_Muller" title="Yvan Muller">Yvan Muller</a> with the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Le%C3%B3n" title="SEAT León">SEAT León</a> TDI in Japan.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 2002, SEAT announced a one-make championship for the new <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Le%C3%B3n" title="SEAT León">SEAT León</a> Cupra R, the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Le%C3%B3n_Supercopa" title="SEAT León Supercopa">SEAT León Supercopa</a>.</p>
<p>In 2004, SEAT with <a href="/wiki/Ray_Mallock_Ltd." class="mw-redirect" title="Ray Mallock Ltd.">Ray Mallock Ltd.</a> (RML) entered the <a href="/wiki/British_Touring_Car_Championship" title="British Touring Car Championship">British Touring Car Championship</a>, running two <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Toledo" title="SEAT Toledo">SEAT Toledo</a> Cupra for former-BTCC Champion <a href="/wiki/Jason_Plato" title="Jason Plato">Jason Plato</a>, and 2003 León UK Champion, <a href="/wiki/Rob_Huff" class="mw-redirect" title="Rob Huff">Rob Huff</a>. In 2005, Huff left to join <a href="/wiki/Chevrolet" title="Chevrolet">Chevrolet</a> (run by RML in the <a href="/wiki/World_Touring_Car_Championship" title="World Touring Car Championship">World Touring Car Championship</a> (WTCC)), and he was replaced by 2004 Leon Champion <a href="/wiki/James_Pickford" title="James Pickford">James Pickford</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Luke_Hines" title="Luke Hines">Luke Hines</a> as SEAT expanded to three cars, now run by Northern South. 2006 saw the Toledo replaced by the new <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Le%C3%B3n" title="SEAT León">León</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Darren_Turner" title="Darren Turner">Darren Turner</a> joined the team with <a href="/wiki/James_Thompson_(racing_driver)" title="James Thompson (racing driver)">James Thompson</a> when his WTCC commitments allowed. 2007 was SEAT's best year in BTCC, as Plato was locked in a season-long battle with <a href="/wiki/Fabrizio_Giovanardi" title="Fabrizio Giovanardi">Fabrizio Giovanardi</a>, which came down to the final race of the season, but just missed out on the title.</p>
<p>Since 2005, SEAT has also competed in the <a href="/wiki/World_Touring_Car_Championship" title="World Touring Car Championship">World Touring Car Championship</a>, with its first best season being 2007, where a failed <a href="/wiki/Water_pump" class="mw-redirect" title="Water pump">water pump</a> robbed <a href="/wiki/Yvan_Muller" title="Yvan Muller">Yvan Muller</a> of certain victory at the final meeting in Macau. SEAT became the first team to run a <a href="/wiki/Turbocharged_Direct_Injection" class="mw-redirect" title="Turbocharged Direct Injection">TDI</a> in the WTCC and this gave them a dominant <a href="/wiki/2008_World_Touring_Car_Championship_season" class="mw-redirect" title="2008 World Touring Car Championship season">2008 World Touring Car Championship season</a>, with Yvan Muller winning the drivers championship. French racing team <a href="/wiki/Oreca" title="Oreca">Oreca</a> cooperates with the WTCC team. SEAT's UK team followed suit in the 2008 BTCC. The BTCC team was sponsored by <a href="/wiki/Holiday_Inn" title="Holiday Inn">Holiday Inn</a>.</p>
