<p>In 2007, SEAT – with the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Le%C3%B3n#1P" title="SEAT León">León Mk2 TDI</a> at the <a href="/wiki/Motorsport_Arena_Oschersleben" title="Motorsport Arena Oschersleben">Motorsport Arena Oschersleben</a> in Germany – became the first manufacturer to win a round of the <a href="/wiki/World_Touring_Car_Championship" title="World Touring Car Championship">World Touring Car Championship</a> (WTCC) series in a diesel car, only a month after announcing it will enter the <a href="/wiki/F%C3%A9d%C3%A9ration_Internationale_de_l%27Automobile" title="Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile">FIA</a> World Touring Car Championship with the León TDI. SEAT's success with the León TDI was continued, and resulted in winning consecutively <a href="/wiki/2008_World_Touring_Car_Championship_season" class="mw-redirect" title="2008 World Touring Car Championship season">2008 World Touring Car Championship</a> and <a href="/wiki/2009_World_Touring_Car_Championship_season" class="mw-redirect" title="2009 World Touring Car Championship season">2009 World Touring Car Championship</a> both titles (for drivers' as well as for manufacturers').</p>
<p>In September 2008, SEAT UK announced that it was to withdraw from all motor sport activity in the UK at the end of the season. The SEAT Cupra Championship and the SEAT BTCC campaign are to end at Brands Hatch on 21 September. BTCC drivers Jason Plato and Darren Turner have been left without drives for 2009. But Plato will drive for Silverline <a href="/wiki/Chevrolet" title="Chevrolet">Chevrolet</a>.</p>
<p>At the opening of the 2009 WTCC, SEAT placed 1st, 2nd, 3rd, and 4th in both races in Brazil.<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80">[80]</a></sup> At the second meeting of the WTCC (in Mexico), the SEAT team placed 1st, 4th, 6th, 7th and 11th in the first race. The second race they placed 1st, 3rd, 7th, and 8th.<sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">[81]</a></sup> While SEAT may have withdrawn from the BTCC, they are showing impressive results in the WTCC.</p>

<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:SEAT_Cupra_GT_cropped.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/SEAT_Cupra_GT_cropped.jpg/220px-SEAT_Cupra_GT_cropped.jpg" width="220" height="84" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/SEAT_Cupra_GT_cropped.jpg/330px-SEAT_Cupra_GT_cropped.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/SEAT_Cupra_GT_cropped.jpg/440px-SEAT_Cupra_GT_cropped.jpg 2x" data-file-width="624" data-file-height="239" /></a>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Grand_tourer_cars">Grand tourer cars</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Grand tourer cars">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In 2003 the SEAT Sport division presented at the Barcelona Motor Show first as a concept car and later the final version of the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Cupra_GT" title="SEAT Cupra GT">SEAT Cupra GT</a> race car, which was produced in limited series on customer demand addressed to expertised individuals and racing teams willing to take part in race events.</p>
<p>The Cupra GT was chosen as a GT race car from racing teams, like the <a href="/wiki/Sunred_Engineering" title="Sunred Engineering">Sunred Engineering (SunRED)</a> team, making its debut in 2004 in the <a href="/wiki/Spanish_GT_Championship" title="Spanish GT Championship">Spanish GT Championship</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">[82]</a></sup> and took part in several <a href="/wiki/Grand_tourer" title="Grand tourer">Grand tourer</a> circuits not only in Spain but also run in tracks abroad like those of <a href="/wiki/Autodromo_Nazionale_Monza" title="Autodromo Nazionale Monza">Monza</a> and <a href="/wiki/Circuit_de_Nevers_Magny-Cours" title="Circuit de Nevers Magny-Cours">Magny-Cours</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">[83]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Formula">Formula</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Formula">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In 1970 SEAT set up the 'Fórmula Nacional' series in Spain,<sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-84">[84]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-85" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-85">[85]</a></sup> a year later to be known as <a href="/wiki/Formula_1430" title="Formula 1430">Formula 1430</a>. The single seater formula cars, which took part driven by young Spanish drivers, were equipped under support from SEAT with engines of the 1430 model and 6700 gearboxes. The first race of the 'Fórmula Nacional' series took place at the Jarama circuit in Madrid.<sup id="cite_ref-media.seat.com_86-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-media.seat.com-86">[86]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-87">[87]</a></sup></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Nomenclature">Nomenclature</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Nomenclature">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>SEAT's corporate tradition, as a Volkswagen Group subsidiary, dictates that the nomenclature of its model range be inspired by Spanish culture. Thus, a large number of SEAT's production models have been named after places in Spain (e.g. <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Arosa" title="SEAT Arosa">Arosa</a>, <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Ibiza" title="SEAT Ibiza">Ibiza</a>, <a href="/wiki/SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba" title="SEAT Córdoba">Córdoba</a>, <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Le%C3%B3n" title="SEAT León">León</a>, <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Toledo" title="SEAT Toledo">Toledo</a>, <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Altea" title="SEAT Altea">Altea</a>, <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Alhambra" title="SEAT Alhambra">Alhambra</a>, <a href="/wiki/SEAT_M%C3%A1laga" title="SEAT Málaga">Málaga</a>, <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Marbella" title="SEAT Marbella">Marbella</a>, <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Ronda" title="SEAT Ronda">Ronda</a> etc.).<sup id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88">[88]</a></sup> However, there have been several exceptions: for example, the name for the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Exeo" title="SEAT Exeo">SEAT Exeo</a> — added to the brand's range in 2008 — was influenced from the Latin word ‘exire’ which means 'to go beyond'.<sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89">[89]</a></sup></p>
<p>Following the marque's naming trend with production models, many of SEAT's concept cars adopted names inspired by either <i>Hispanic dances</i> (e.g. <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Tango" title="SEAT Tango">Tango</a>, <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Bolero" title="SEAT Bolero">Bolero</a>, <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Salsa" title="SEAT Salsa">Salsa</a>), abbreviations related to existing production models (e.g. IBZ for Ibiza, IBE for 'Ibiza Eléctrico',<sup id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-90">[90]</a></sup> TL for Toledo etc.), or even names reminiscent of SEAT's historic sporting roots (e.g. <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Formula" class="mw-redirect" title="SEAT Formula">Fórmula</a>, <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Cupra_GT" title="SEAT Cupra GT">Cupra GT</a>).</p>
<p>Moreover, in recent years, special versions of the production models' specific ranges have been added, such as the <b>SC</b> or <i>SportCoupé</i> edition, <sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">[91]</a></sup>) or <b>ST</b> (for <i>SportTourer</i><sup id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-92">[92]</a></sup>) differentiating the 3-door and the estate versions from the standard 4/5-door ones, while the <b>Cupra</b>, or <i>Cup Racing</i> edition <sup id="cite_ref-93" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93">[93]</a></sup>) and <b>FR</b> (for <i>Fórmula Racing</i><sup id="cite_ref-94" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-94">[94]</a></sup>) has been used for the high-performance models in the range, signalising SEAT's positioning as a sport-oriented brand<sup id="cite_ref-media.seat.com_86-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-media.seat.com-86">[86]</a></sup> involved in racing.</p>
<p>Historic references can be found with the iconic <b>'Bocanegra'</b> name, meaning 'black mouth' in Spanish, which accompanies the Ibiza model and has its origins in the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_1200_Sport" title="SEAT 1200 Sport">SEAT 1200 Sport</a>, the original 'SEAT Bocanegra' due to its black painted fascia in the front.<sup id="cite_ref-95" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-95">[95]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Sub-ranges">Sub-ranges</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Sub-ranges">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<dl>
<dt>'Ecomotive' range</dt>
</dl>
<p>Almost every model in SEAT's range has an '<a href="/wiki/Ecomotive" class="mw-redirect" title="Ecomotive">Ecomotive</a>' derivative version, which in comparison to the standard version has a more eco-friendly tuning.<sup id="cite_ref-96" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-96">[96]</a></sup> Reduction of weight, low-resistance tyres, new aerodynamics, tweaks in the suspension,<sup id="cite_ref-97" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-97">[97]</a></sup> as well as changes made to the engine's electronic management software with an additional implementation of a maintenance-free<sup id="cite_ref-98" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-98">[98]</a></sup> Diesel Particle Filter (DPF) for the diesel engines, also updates in the gearbox and the gear ratios with a gearshift indicator in the dash panel reminding when it is the proper time to change gears, combined with an engine 'Start/Stop system' and an 'Energy Recuperation system' are some of the modifications adopted in the Ecomotive range in order to cut down both fuel consumption and emissions.<sup id="cite_ref-99" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-99">[99]</a></sup> The result is a range with some of the cleanest models<sup id="cite_ref-100" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-100">[100]</a></sup> featuring an improvement not only in gas and particles emissions but also in fuel economy, without big compromise in the vehicle's dynamic performance or practicality; for example the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Ibiza" title="SEAT Ibiza">SEAT Ibiza</a> Ecomotive 1.4 TDI has CO<sub>2</sub> emissions coming up at 98 g/km<sup id="cite_ref-101" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-101">[101]</a></sup> and still it comes even faster from 0 to 100&#160;km/h than the standard version<sup id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102">[102]</a></sup> featuring a 5-door body and air-conditioning, while the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Le%C3%B3n" title="SEAT León">SEAT León</a> Ecomotive's CO<sub>2</sub> emissions are among the lowest in its segment too and raise up to 99 g/km.<sup id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-103">[103]</a></sup> Up to the present, the Ecomotive range has been renowned in many occasions. In 2008, the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Ibiza" title="SEAT Ibiza">Ibiza</a> Ecomotive has been declared on top of the Verkehrs-Club Deutschland’s 2008/2009 list in the “environmentally beneficial vehicle” category<sup id="cite_ref-104" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-104">[104]</a></sup> and in the 10th Eco Tour not only it has won in the small diesel class but also proved to be the overall winner of all categories.<sup id="cite_ref-105" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-105">[105]</a></sup> In that specific year the SEAT Ibiza Ecomotive was also awarded with the 'Ecobest 2008' award <sup id="cite_ref-106" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-106">[106]</a></sup> by the Autobest organisation and the German newspaper Bild am Sonntag named it the 'most economic car of its class in the world'.<sup id="cite_ref-107" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-107">[107]</a></sup> The year 2009 has been the one when once more the Ibiza Ecomotive was nominated for the 'Green Steering wheel' award in Switzerland,<sup id="cite_ref-108" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-108">[108]</a></sup> and has set two consecutive times a new world record on fuel saving with a single tank, certified by the IPMC (International Police Motor Corporation)&#160;: the first when the Austrian Gerhard Plattner drove from Martorell (Spain) to Göttingen (Germany) with an average fuel consumption of 2.9 l/100&#160;km<sup id="cite_ref-109" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-109">[109]</a></sup> and the second time in his route from Cieszyn (Poland) to Frankfurt (Germany) having achieved the world record in fuel consumption of 2.34 l/100&#160;km (or 100 mpg U.S.<sup id="cite_ref-110" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-110">[110]</a></sup>) covering a distance of 1,910&#160;km on a single tank.<sup id="cite_ref-111" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-111">[111]</a></sup></p>
<dl>
<dt>'MultiFuel' range</dt>
</dl>
<p>The MultiFuel range consists in the introduction of the <a href="/wiki/Flexible-fuel_vehicle" title="Flexible-fuel vehicle">flexible-fuel vehicle</a> bio-ethanol technology in selected SEAT models — i.e., the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Le%C3%B3n" title="SEAT León">SEAT León MultiFuel</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-112" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-112">[112]</a></sup> the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Altea" title="SEAT Altea">SEAT Altea MultiFuel</a><sup id="cite_ref-113" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-113">[113]</a></sup> and the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Altea_XL" class="mw-redirect" title="SEAT Altea XL">SEAT Altea XL MultiFuel</a><sup id="cite_ref-114" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-114">[114]</a></sup> — with the implementation of the 1.6 MPI MultiFuel E85 motor, capable of producing exactly the same horsepower (102&#160;bhp) just like the relevant pure petrol version of the engine.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Sales_and_production_figures">Sales and production figures</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Sales and production figures">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Since its beginnings in 1953, more than 16 million SEAT cars have been produced with the most successful product in the range being the SEAT Ibiza, a model which has sold over 4 million units in its four generations up to the present.<sup id="cite_ref-115" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-115">[115]</a></sup></p>
<p>In the year 2009, the total annual retail sales number of SEAT cars was 336,683 vehicles,<sup id="cite_ref-KeyFigures_116-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-KeyFigures-116">[116]</a></sup> while the annual production of vehicles under the SEAT brand came up to 307,502 units (301,287 made in SEAT's Martorell plant and 6,215 in other Volkswagen group's factories).</p>
<p>The total production per year of SEAT cars, manufactured in SEAT and other Volkswagen group's plants, is shown in the following table (not comprising cars of other Volkswagen group's brands, produced in SEAT-owned facilities)&#160;:</p>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Rebadges">Rebadges</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Rebadges">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Under Volkswagen Group's ownership, numerous SEAT models have been rebadged under other brands, either inside the Volkswagen Group's portfolio or out of it.</p>
<p>In particular some examples, concerning the rebadges deriving from SEAT models and being carried out under other Volkswagen Group's brands, are the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Ibiza" title="SEAT Ibiza">SEAT Ibiza Mk2</a> which has been rebadged under the VW brand as the <a href="/wiki/VW_Polo_Playa" class="mw-redirect" title="VW Polo Playa">VW Polo Playa</a>, the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_C%C3%B3rdoba" title="SEAT Córdoba">SEAT Córdoba Mk1</a> rebadged as the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Polo_Mk3" title="Volkswagen Polo Mk3">VW Polo Classic</a> — <a href="/wiki/FAW-VW_Automobile" class="mw-redirect" title="FAW-VW Automobile">FAW-VW City-Golf</a> — <a href="/wiki/VW_Derby" class="mw-redirect" title="VW Derby">VW Derby</a>, the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Arosa" title="SEAT Arosa">SEAT Arosa</a> as the <a href="/wiki/VW_Lupo" class="mw-redirect" title="VW Lupo">VW Lupo</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Inca" title="SEAT Inca">SEAT Inca</a> as the <a href="/wiki/VW_Caddy" class="mw-redirect" title="VW Caddy">VW Caddy</a>.</p>
<p>Further rebadges have come under non Volkswagen Group brand ranges and some notable examples are the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Ibiza" title="SEAT Ibiza">SEAT Ibiza Mk1</a> which has been rebadged as the <a href="/wiki/Nanjing_Yuejin_Soyat" title="Nanjing Yuejin Soyat">Nanjing Yuejin Eagle NJ6400-Unique NJ6400-Soyat NJ7150-Soyat Unique NJ1020</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Toledo" title="SEAT Toledo">SEAT Toledo Mk1</a> as the <a href="/wiki/Chery_A11" title="Chery A11">Chery A11-Fulwin-Fengyun-Windcloud</a> — <a href="/wiki/Chery_A15" title="Chery A15">Chery A15-A168-Amulet-Cowin-Qiyun-Flagcloud</a> — <a href="/wiki/TagAZ" title="TagAZ">Vortex Corda</a> .</p>
<p>On the other hand, several SEAT models have derived as rebadges coming from other Volkswagen Group's brands such as the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Alhambra" title="SEAT Alhambra">SEAT Alhambra Mk1 and Mk2</a> respectively from the <a href="/wiki/VW_Sharan" class="mw-redirect" title="VW Sharan">VW Sharan Mk1 and Mk2</a> (the first generation resulting after a joint venture of the Volkswagen Group together with <a href="/wiki/Ford_Galaxy" title="Ford Galaxy">Ford</a>) and the <a href="/wiki/SEAT_Exeo" title="SEAT Exeo">SEAT Exeo</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Audi_A4" title="Audi A4">Audi A4 B7</a>.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Tuning_companies">Tuning companies</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: Tuning companies">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Several tuning companies have produced modified or high-performance versions of various SEAT models, some significant examples among those being <a href="/wiki/Abt_Sportsline" title="Abt Sportsline">Abt Sportsline</a>, <a href="/wiki/Je_Design" title="Je Design">Je Design</a>, MTM (Motoren Technik Mayer), <a href="/wiki/Abarth" title="Abarth">Abarth</a>, Emelba, Annibal etc.</p>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Future_models">Future models</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Future models">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>According to the president of SEAT, James Muir, in an interview with the Spanish daily newspaper <i><a href="/wiki/El_Mundo_(Spain)" title="El Mundo (Spain)">El Mundo</a></i> in October 2010,<sup id="cite_ref-133" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-133">[129]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-134" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-134">[130]</a></sup></p>
<p>SEAT scheduling comprises the following future models in the near future:<sup id="cite_ref-135" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-135">[131]</a></sup></p>
<ul>
<li>SEAT León Mk3 (3-door/5-door/estate), in Q4 2012</li>
<li>SEAT Exeo Mk2 or its replacement based on I<b>BL</b> could be named <b>B</b>o<b>L</b>ero</li>
</ul>
<p>There is still thinking of a <a href="/wiki/Compact_MPV" title="Compact MPV">compact MPV</a> car successor to the Altea, and a <a href="/wiki/SUV" class="mw-redirect" title="SUV">SUV</a> model on the basis of the SEAT IBX concept car.<sup id="cite_ref-136" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-136">[132]</a></sup></p>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Leadership">Leadership</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=29" title="Edit section: Leadership">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Environmental_policy">Environmental policy</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=31" title="Edit section: Environmental policy">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<dl>
<dt>Electric and hybrid technology development</dt>
</dl>
<p>Since the early 1990s, SEAT has developed and presented several prototypes with either full electric or hybrid powertrain, including the SEAT Toledo Mk1 electric model (1992), the SEAT Ibiza Mk2 electric car (1993), the SEAT Inca electric van (1995), the SEAT León Mk2 Twin drive (2009), the SEAT IBE concept (2010) and the SEAT IBX concept SUV (2011) hybrid cars.<sup id="cite_ref-142" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-142">[138]</a></sup></p>
<dl>
<dt>‘SEAT al Sol’ project</dt>
</dl>
<p>The ‘SEAT al Sol’ project consists in the integration of use of solar power through a system of <a href="/wiki/Solar_panel" title="Solar panel">photovoltaic panels</a> generating electricity in SEAT's factory in Martorell. The project is going to be carried through in collaboration with GA-Solar from the beginnings of 2010, covering a factory area of 320,000 m2 with a system of more than 10 MW of photovoltaic panels. This installation is expected to produce more than 13 million kwh of electricity annually, aimed at reducing greenhouse gas emissions by over 6,200 tonnes of CO<sub>2</sub> per year.<sup id="cite_ref-media.seat.com.2Fen_143-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-media.seat.com.2Fen-143">[139]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-144" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-144">[140]</a></sup></p>
<dl>
<dt>‘Cenit verde’ project</dt>
</dl>
<p>The Cenit VERDE initiative is a research project backed by the CENIT (the National Strategic Consortia for Technical Research) programme and supported by the Spanish Ministry of Science and Innovation, in which SEAT plays a key role. Aiming at developing technologies, components and infrastructure for hybrid and electrically powered cars in Spain, this programme brings together 16 technology companies (including Siemens, Endesa, Iberdrola, REE, Cegasa, Ficosa, Circuitor, Cobra or Lear) and 16 universities and research establishments under the CTM coordination (Centre Tecnològic in Manresa)<sup id="cite_ref-145" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-145">[141]</a></sup> and the support of the CDTI (Centre for Industrial Technological Development, an organization pertaining to the Ministry of Science and Innovation).</p>
<p>In January 2010, the Cenit Verde association made its opening meeting at SEAT's Technical Centre in Martorell.<sup id="cite_ref-146" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-146">[142]</a></sup></p>
<p>As part of its contribution SEAT comes in with its own 'Verde' pre-project, including the technology implemented in the plug-in hybrid <b><a href="/wiki/SEAT_Le%C3%B3n_Twin_drive" class="mw-redirect" title="SEAT León Twin drive">SEAT León Twin drive</a></b><sup id="cite_ref-147" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-147">[143]</a></sup> as well as in the <b><a href="/wiki/SEAT_IBE" title="SEAT IBE">SEAT IBE</a> concept</b> zero emissions electric vehicle presented in the 2010 Geneva motor show.<sup id="cite_ref-148" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-148">[144]</a></sup></p>
<dl>
<dt>‘SEAT Autometro’ project</dt>
</dl>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:TMD_a_Castellbisbal_Ferrocarrils_de_la_Generalitat_de_Catalunya.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/TMD_a_Castellbisbal_Ferrocarrils_de_la_Generalitat_de_Catalunya.jpg/220px-TMD_a_Castellbisbal_Ferrocarrils_de_la_Generalitat_de_Catalunya.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/TMD_a_Castellbisbal_Ferrocarrils_de_la_Generalitat_de_Catalunya.jpg/330px-TMD_a_Castellbisbal_Ferrocarrils_de_la_Generalitat_de_Catalunya.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/TMD_a_Castellbisbal_Ferrocarrils_de_la_Generalitat_de_Catalunya.jpg/440px-TMD_a_Castellbisbal_Ferrocarrils_de_la_Generalitat_de_Catalunya.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3264" data-file-height="2448" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:TMD_a_Castellbisbal_Ferrocarrils_de_la_Generalitat_de_Catalunya.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
A TMD (Teco Media Distancia) cargo train on its way from SEAT's Martorell plant.<sup id="cite_ref-149" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-149">[145]</a></sup></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The ‘SEAT Autometro’ project comprises the construction and management of a rail link service between SEAT's Martorell complex and the <a href="/wiki/Port_of_Barcelona" title="Port of Barcelona">Port of Barcelona</a>, in the aim of transport of vehicles and components. Autometro is the joint-venture company which operates the rail, having <a href="/wiki/Ferrocarrils_de_la_Generalitat_de_Catalunya" title="Ferrocarrils de la Generalitat de Catalunya">Ferrocarrils de la Generalitat de Catalunya (FGC)</a> local rail company, <a href="/wiki/COMSA" title="COMSA">COMSA Rail Transport</a> and Pecovasa as its shareholders. The company was founded in November 2005 almost five months after an initial agreement was signed between the <a href="/wiki/Catalan_government" class="mw-redirect" title="Catalan government">Catalan government</a> (<a href="/wiki/Generalitat" title="Generalitat">Generalitat</a>), the Barcelona Port Authority and SEAT.<sup id="cite_ref-150" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-150">[146]</a></sup> Due to this project, a branch connecting the Martorell plant with the <a href="/wiki/Llobregat%E2%80%93Anoia_line" class="mw-redirect" title="Llobregat–Anoia line">FGC 'Llobregat-Anoia' main rail line</a> had to be constructed, as well as further adaptations to the transport network and the host infrastructures in the Port of Barcelona had to be made. The budget for the project comes up to 6.8 million euro, while SEAT on its part also assumes the operational transport costs.<sup id="cite_ref-151" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-151">[147]</a></sup><br />
The use of this rail link since January 18, 2008, instead of road transport, has helped not only in terms of cost effectiveness and road safety but also in the reduction of both road congestion and greenhouse gas emissions.<br />
Over the whole 'Autometro' project awards have been given for the best logistics idea at the 2007 International Logistics Fair (SIL) and specifically to SEAT as the 2008 Distinguished loader by the Loaders’ Association of the Port of Barcelona.<sup id="cite_ref-152" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-152">[148]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sponsorship">Sponsorship</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=32" title="Edit section: Sponsorship">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>SEAT has been a sponsor in major sports events, such as</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/UEFA_Europa_League" title="UEFA Europa League">UEFA Europa League</a><sup id="cite_ref-153" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-153">[149]</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Red_Bull" title="Red Bull">Red Bull</a> <a href="/wiki/Red_Bull_Air_Race" class="mw-redirect" title="Red Bull Air Race">Air Race</a> World Championship<sup id="cite_ref-154" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-154">[150]</a></sup></li>
<li>Davis Cup World Group Final<sup id="cite_ref-155" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-155">[151]</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/1992_Summer_Olympics" title="1992 Summer Olympics">Barcelona 1992</a> <a href="/wiki/Olympic_Games" title="Olympic Games">Olympic Games</a><sup id="cite_ref-156" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-156">[152]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-157" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-157">[153]</a></sup></li>
<li>Eintracht Braunschweig</li>
</ul>
<p>The company was one of the prime sponsors of <a href="/wiki/Tunisia%27s_national_basketball_team" class="mw-redirect" title="Tunisia's national basketball team">Tunisia's national basketball team</a> at the <a href="/wiki/2015_FIBA_Africa_Championship" class="mw-redirect" title="2015 FIBA Africa Championship">2015 FIBA Africa Championship</a> where the company's logo was regularly displayed (e.g. on the team's shorts).<sup id="cite_ref-158" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-158">[154]</a></sup></p>
<p>Further, SEAT is a strong supporter of artists, like <a href="/wiki/Shakira" title="Shakira">Shakira</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-159" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-159">[155]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Armin_van_Buuren" title="Armin van Buuren">Armin van Buuren</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-160" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-160">[156]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/David_Guetta" title="David Guetta">David Guetta</a><sup id="cite_ref-161" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-161">[157]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-162" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-162">[158]</a></sup> etc.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Awards">Awards</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SEAT&amp;action=edit&amp;section=33" title="Edit section: Awards">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Over the years the SEAT marque has been honoured with several awards, such as</p>
<ul>
<li>The Landaben plant, 100% owned by SEAT, S.A. by that time, received in 1986 the <i>World quality award (Q-86)</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-163" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-163">[159]</a></sup></li>
<li>The Martorell plant, 100% owned by SEAT, S.A., received in 1998 the <i>Best factory of the VW Group in the first quarter award</i>.</li>
<li>The Barcelona 'Gearbox del Prat' plant, 100% owned by SEAT, S.A., received in 2009 the <i>Volkswagen Excellence award</i> for its high-quality manufacturing process and product.<sup id="cite_ref-Gearbox_del_Prat_25-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gearbox_del_Prat-25">[25]</a></sup></li>
<li>The SEAT brand itself in 2009 has been named <i>'Most Improved Used Car Brand of the decade'</i> in the CAP Used Car of the Decade Awards.<sup id="cite_ref-164" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-164">[160]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-165" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-165">[161]</a></sup></li>
<li><i>'AvD Innovationspreis 2006'</i> award for technological innovations developed at the SEAT Technical Centre in Martorell, from the German automobile club 'Automobilclub von Deutschland' (AvD)<sup id="cite_ref-166" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-166">[162]</a></sup></li>
<li>In the 2007 Barcelona International motor show SEAT received two <i>awards for the best technological innovations in the automotive sector</i>, for the LED modules implementation in headlights and the project of virtual fabrication and applied ergonomics.<sup id="cite_ref-167" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-167">[163]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-168" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-168">[164]</a></sup></li>
<li><i>'Best project in the use of an electronic signature in the private sector in 2008'</i> for SEAT’s electronic invoicing system, by the Catalan Certification Agency (CATCert)<sup id="cite_ref-169" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-169">[165]</a></sup></li>
<li><i>'Best logistics initiative 2007'</i> award for the SEAT-Autometro project, by the International Logistics Salon<sup id="cite_ref-170" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-170">[166]</a></sup></li>
<li><i>'Port of Barcelona’s Distinguished Loader prize in 2008'</i> , by the Port of Barcelona’s Loaders’ Association<sup id="cite_ref-171" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-171">[167]</a></sup></li>
</ul>
